{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_aetna_ver02/data/sn92060454/00393346759/1945082501/0145.xml":{"full_text":"30% 39nton 3^tmcg\nOfEcia! Publication of the Connecticut State Building Trades\nand Construction Council\nOfBcial Publication of T\\te New Haven Central Labor Council\nAHiiiated With the American Federation of Labor\nPublished Weekly\nLABOR'S OWN PAPER\nLabor Temple, 135-139 Goffe Street, New Haven 11, Conn.\nDial: 6-6245\nEditorial Control and Ownership\u2014-As the official publication of the New\nHaven Central Labor Council, the editorial and advertising policy of T&E\nUNION TIMES are under the supervision of the officers and Executive Board\nof the Council. They are Vincent J. McGovern, President; Richard Buckley,\nVice-President; John Redmond, Recording Secretary; August F. Striby,\nFinancial Secretary; Barbers Union, No. 215, Frank Spadola; Machinists\nUmion, No. 420, Alfred E Murphy; Musicians Union, No. 234, Harry F.\nBenson; Railroad Lodge, No. 6161, Leonard Reed; Carpenters Union, No.\n79, George H. Riehm; Trolleymen's Union, Frank Carr and Samuel F.\nCurry; Painters Union, William Enright and Saul Kreas. This newspaper\nis published by THE UNION TiMEs, INC., whose ofhcers are Harold V. Fein\nmark, President; Nathan Sherman, Secretary; and Leonard Farmer,\nTreasurer.\nNathan Sherman, Editor\nSubacription Rates\n52 Issues, $1.75; 26 Issues, $1.00\nThe People\u2014The Court of Last Resort\nNEW HAVEN, CONN., SATURDAY, AUGUST 25, 1945\nFrom Contusion To Chaos\nFrom confusion to chaos is the best way to describe the\neffect of the sudden ending of the Pacific War on postwar\nplans. Before the abrupt ending of hostilities it was thought\nthat time would permit Washington to muddle through with\nsome kind of minimum program. Now the bottom has sud\ndenly dropped out and revealed for everybody to see\u2014our\nhomefront Pearl Harbor.\nSynthetic optimism is the keynote sounded most frequently\nin Washington now. Topside Washington officials greet one\nanother with a sickly grin and mutter something like \"the\nnatural resilience of the economy will take care of every\nthing. Oh, yes, we may have something like eight million\nunemployed by spring but it will be only temporary.\"\nThe blunt truth of the matter is that, as labor people have\nbeen saying until they are blue in the face, economically we\nare completely unprepared for the problems raised by the\nend of the war.\nusten to some 01 tne Key ngures in me 8!tuanon:\n1. As of April 1945, there were more than 12 million men\nand women in the armed forces. Seven million at least are\nto be demobilized within the next year.\n2. As of the end of June 1945, there were eight million\nworkers engaged in direct munitions production, to say\nnothing of workers engaged in supporting activities which\nthis figure does not include. Plans call for the immediate\ncutback of more than 90% of total procurement.\n3. The official estimates predict unemployment of more\nthan five millions by the end of the year and eight millions\nby spring of 1946.\n4. IFhaf nobody has said pubHcFy so /ar is that, under the\nmost /avorabfe conditions, our economy has never been abie\nto increase employment by more than 3 miiiions per year\u2014\nand that unemployment has never been reduced by more than\n2% millions per year. Fn the absence o/ herculean ej^orts,\nthis means that it Mill take several years be/ore the unem\nployed are absorbed\u2014assuming the capacity o/ industry to\naccomplish this.\n5. fn 1940 there were about 50 million people working, fn\n1945 there are something short of 64 millions working and\nin the armed forces. Allowing for the maximum withdrawal\nof workers from the labor market after complete demobili\nzation of the armed forces, we shall still need to find jobs\nfor 13 to 15 million more workers than were employed in\n1940, our last peacetime year.\nAll of these facts clearly point to a situation in 1945 and\n1946 which will not be met by \"a return to normalcy\" and\n\"letting things take their course.\" A return to normalcy spells\ndisaster\u2014unless we catch on right quickly that government\nwill have to exercise a positive role in finding jobs for every\none who wants to work.\n(jouernors Fear JoMess BiH\nSeldom, if ever, have Congressmen been called back to resume a\nsession with such an urgent and pressing agenda as will be presented\nto the Senators and Reprsentatives on September 5, when they recon\nvene after a vacation.\nFirst in the eyes of the great majority of the voters will be to get\naction on improving unemployment compensation payments, at a na\ntionwide maximum of $25 for a period of at least 26 weeks. In addi\ntion, bills by Sen. Harley Kilgore (D., W. Va.) and Aime J. Forand\n(D., R. would provide transportation expenses home for migrant\nwar workers, and would raise the benefits to unemployed veterans above\nthe $20 a week now guaranteed in the GI Bill of Rights.\nViolent pressure by the state governors, who have a delegation now\nin Washington which has seen President Truman and which is button\nholing Congressmen, is expected to cause a bitter fight on jobless bene\nfits legislation. The governors, several of them accompanied by their\nstate Unemployment Compensation Directors, are violently opposed to\nany \"federalization\" of the jobless benefits system, though they are\nwilling to take federal funds. Southern governors, in particular, don't\nwant high jobless benefits paid because it might serve to force wage\nrates up to decent levels in many communities. Hungry workers are use\nful to them in keeping labor \"docile\" and \"in its place.\"\nCounter-pressure from organized workers is expected to be strong.\nDirctor of War Mobilization and Reconversion John Snyder has listed\nthe unemployment compensation measure at the top of his list of\nneeded Congressional action. President Truman and Senate Majority\nLeader Alben Barkley have also been outspoken on the need for the law.\nKEEPtNG )M600DSP)R)TS\nSpecial\nPrivilege\nMend of\nStraight\nWHISKIES\n$3.23\nFifth\nGaHagher Burton^ Q. 4 8\nVV ^\"th\nPHILADELPHIA\n$3\n.88\nFifth\nCARSTAIRS\n\u20ac0.46\nJ Fifth\nLANSDOWNE\n$3\n.86\nFifth\nFLEISCHMANN'S\n$3\n.54\nFifth\nHUNTER\n.22\nFifth\n1128 CHAPEL ST., at York\n332 NEWHALL ST., at Read\n99 FARREN AVE., at Fulton\nTel. 6-0600\nTel. 6-6046\nTel. 4-1840\nTime To Stef? On It J\n(By Baer)\nAYE, AYE, St R/\nFETCH ON THOSE,\nPOST WAR PLANS/\nWE'RE A LITTLE LATE\nBUT LETS GET GOING//\n\nAs We See !t, by The Staff\n(Continued from Page One)\nCittzen-Dcmocrat, as shown in this\nheading:\n28 LOCAL YOKELS\nOFF TO THE WAR\n\n\"NO wonder we see only their\nheads,\" commented a friend when\nhe read the foilowing note in the\n/ac&gonriife Florida Times:\n\"Speaking of tail foiks\u2014Alexis\nSmith has never worn anything but\nher stockings or baiiet siippers for\nclose-ups with her leading men.\"\nW\nWHEN a politaxer needs a\nfriend, he can always count on the\nKu Klux Klan to put in a kind\nword for him. Sen. Theodore Bilbo\n(D, Miss.), whose poison pen let\nter writing campaign to supporters\nof FEPC has brought demands for\nhis immediate impeachment, got a\npat on the back at the last meeting\nof the KKK in Wichita, Kans.\nA resolution was unanimously\nadopted requesting \"all members\nto write letters of commendation\nto him for his courageous behavior\nin behalf of true Americanism.\"\n\nAT LEAST 15 industrial com\nmunitities throughout the country\nare on the brink of serious interra\ncial clashes, according to recent\nstudies made by the American\nCouncil on Race Relations. This\nwas disclosed by Director A. A.\nLiveright in a speech at the Univer\nsity of Chicago in which he warned\nthat \"increasing tensions in inter\ngroup relations stress the need for\na new approach to race problems/'\n\"The race relation question must\nbe taken out of classrooms and\nwelfare agencies and must deal with\nneighborhood and street corned\nsituations,\" he said.\n\"Bilbos, Cerald Smiths and Ran\nkins must not be allowed to influ\nence the mass of people. We must\nbring about changes in attitudes to\nachieve the more practical and con\ncrete ends which we desire.\"\n5-4123\nTeHow Cab\nPHOTOGRAPHS\nANYWHERE\nDAY OR NIGHT\nDinners, Receptions, Weddings,\nLodges, Home Portraits of Chil\ndren, Outings. No group too\nlarge.\nCHAPEL STUDIO\nPHONE 6-4268\nChape! State Sts.\n(Over LIggett's)\nNOTICE\nVeterans On!y\nCertified Trade School. Your future\ndepends on your knowledge, take\nadvantage of this opportunity.\nUnder the G. 1. Bill of Rights, you\nare no doubt entitfed to educa\ntional benefits that will help you fit\nyourself for operating your own\nbusiness, or higher paying positions\nopen in this vast field.\nIf you come under ^his bill, Uncle\nSam will pay for your tuition, in\nany approved school or college that\nyou may select.\nIt is understood that you will re\nceive subsistence for living ex\npenses while in training.\nThis is an opportunity to become\nindependent for the rest of your\nINVESTIGATE NOW\nrractica! Schooi\nof Welding\nENROLLMENT OFFICES\nAT ROOM 207\nIS2 TEMPLE STREET\nNEW HAVEN, CONN.\nTEL. NOS. 7-3789\n7-1633\nCarpenters A/e/p\nVets On *Sxt Dotun\nSAN DIEGO, Calif.\u2014(FP)\nDoubling its original goal of 250\nunits, Local 1300, United Bro.\nof Carpenters has completed a\nunique venture into the furni\nture-manufacturing business by\nproducing more than 500 Cape\nCod chairs for convalescent sol\ndiers of the Mitchell army hos\npital near here.\nvotunteers ot the unton de\nvoted all their weekends since\nJune 1 to fabricating and as\nsembling the outdoor-type\nchairs, using lumber donated by\n'various local Arms. San Diego's\nfour major shipyards provided\nfacilities for the project.\nMaj. Gen. Charles H. Lyman,\nretired Marine ofRcer who heads\nthe local Red Cross chapter\nwhich requested the union's aid,\nhas expressed his oHicial grati\ntude at the efforts of the men.\nA SUBHEAD on the AP s Flashes\nof Life column recently startled\nmany a wide-awake copy reader.\nThe item concerned \"a plump,\nmotherly appearing woman who\nreturned two ration books and con\nfessed she had misrepresented her\nself as a mother of three. She was\nquoted as saying \"I'm unmarried\nand Heaven knows 1 have no chil\ndren.\" The subhead: \"Clean\nBreast.\"\nBACK in the Why-Don't We\nRead-Fiiiers-More-CarefuHy Depart\nment, the Bridgeport (Conn.)\nBoat reported: \"A cofd is about\nthree-fourths its mature height at\nbirth.\"\n\nA RURAL correspondent of the\nPort Arthur (Tex.) Afews has given\nthe State Editor the idea for a\n\"talkie edition.\" He submitted a\n\"P\" DAY\nShould mean more than Pay\nDay to you Fire, Accident.\nHospitalization and Life Insur\nance wiH continue your pay\nday. See\nDavid A. Goldberg\n\"A Proven Friend oi Labor\"\n207 ORANGE STREET\n8-5207 NEW HAVEN, CONN.\nstory of which he was proud and\nappended: \"If possible, please\nprint this verbally.\"\ni\nTHE Los Angeles Times comes\nthrough with a headline for \"Hor\nrible Thought Department:\"\nBERLIN SOCIETY WOMEN\nSERVE YANKS FOR FOOD\n\nj AN ITEM in the Fancoucer\n(B. C.) Daily Province reported:\n\"A lumber thief who called with a\ntruck stole about 1,000 feet of\nand a 14-piece of etaoinrdluu ship\nlap.\"\n\nTHE picture of a white-haired\nwoman and a young girl appeared\non the New York Sun's society page\nthe other day beneath the caption:\n\"Newly Married Couple.\"\nt \"THE American public doesn't\nlike General Franco any better to\nday than seven years ago,\" says a\nrecent Gaiiup poll comparing pres\nent attitudes toward the Spanish\ndictator with those current during\nthe Spanish Civil War. When asked\nwhether they would like to see\nSpain made a member of the Unit\ned Nations, under Franco's govern\nment, 76% said \"no!\"\nHack Drivers Join\nTeamsters Union\nWASHINGTON (FP) Some\n100 members of the Associated Taxi\ncab Operators, an independent organi\nzation, have voted to affiliate with\nthe Inti. Bro. of Teamsters.\nSec. E. Erwin Dollar said the newly\nchartered A.F.L. union would seek\nto keep 8,000 Washington hack drivers\nfrom being caught \"unorganized as\nthe wind when the war ends.\"\nFor local and world-wide\nnews that happened during\nthe night listen to\nCHAMBERLAINS\n8:00 A. M. Newscast\nMonday thru Saturdays\nWNHC\n1340 On Your Dial\nWe're ready to\nstart 'em bach\nto school\nsmardy dressed 1\n(at budget-helping prices)\nOn The Scene\nIn\nWashington\nBy Travis K. Hedrick\nOne compilation of figures on\nforthcoming jobiessness released\nhere predicted 7 million out of\nwork by Christmas in the transi\ntion from war to peacetime employ\nment.\nT^is 7 million figure is the work\nof economists of separate agencies,\nand the men said they believed a\nfigure of 8 or 9 million may be\nreached in 1946.\nAgainst this official release filtered\nthrough the red tape of the OWI\nnews desk, your reporter has seen a\nmore complete set of figures made\nup by still another agency that must\nremain unmentioned which sets 10\nmillion as the estimate for December,\n1945 and says that four million of\nthese will be out of work by Septem\nber.\nOnly Temporary\nme most re-assurmg thing about\nboth sets of statements is that they\nagree that this mass unemployment\n\"will not be alarming\" if it is only\ntemporary.\nSure to feel the impact of this wave\nof unemployment at full flood will be\nDetroit and Seattle among the larger\ncities\u2014and such war boom towns as\nPascagoula, Miss, with its giant\nshipyards, and Huntsville, Ala. with\nits textiles.)\nOverall, the unpleasant pros\npect is that one in ten U S. bread\nwinners (not counting the tempor\nary workers, wives and transient\nemployes) will be looking for a job\nby the end of the year. In some\ncities the figure will be higher;\nThe total of 10 million is only\n3 million short of the low point of\nthe Hoover depression when we had\n13 million jobless back in 1932.\nNow that the crisis has come, the\nvarious federal agencies are in a\ndither issuing anonymous estimates\nof the size of the army of unem\nBUY WAR BONDS\nBeauty depends\non quality\nIt Is a common mistake\nto judge the value of\na diamond by its size\nonly. The fact is that\nbrilliance and beauty\ndo not depend upon\nsize, but on the quality\nof the gem itself.\nIf you'd like to know\nmore about diamonds\nbefore you buy, drop\nin for a chat about\nthem with us. There\nis no obligation.\n/7/nstrafe(7\u2014Engagement r/ng wntA\n7*rt/7:ant f/tamonf% an(7 /onr cnt\nrEamonJs. #270. Prtce tnc/ndes\nEe<7era/ ta^.\nKIRBY'S\n/fwchrr /or Ooor <t Confmry\n972 CHAPEL ST.\nNew Haven To HoM\n\"Protest Meeting\"\n(Continued from Page One)\ncent J. McGovern, president of the\nN. H. Centra! Labor Counci!, and\nEdward J. McCrone, C.LO. direc\ntor, associate chairman; A!fred\nVigneau!t, E!ectricians Union,\nAFL, executive secretary; Nathan\nSherman, editor of The Union\nTimes, pubiic re!ations secretary.\nP!ans for the meeting were made\nat a meeting held Wednesday night,\nwhich, in addition to those above, was\nalso attended by Richard Buckley,\nAFL; Joseph Ciazzi and William\nSkolnick, CIO; Mrs. Ruth Banks,\npresident of the New' Haven Branch\nof the National Association for the\nAdvancement of Colored People.\nProgram\nThe legislative measure which\nthe committee will present to the\nmass meeting for approval are:\nI* Murray Full Employment\n2. Expansion of unemployment\ncoverage, as proposed by Persident\nTruman.\n3. The Wagner Public Hous\n!ng Program.\n4. A National Medical Care\nProgram, and expanded Social Se\ncurity Legislation (Murray-Wag\nner-Dingall Act).\n5. Agricultural legislation to\nhelp farmers in the post-war pe\nriod.\n6. Fair Employment Practices\nAct.\nployed. Those estimates were avail\nable, if they could be pried loose,\nmonths and months ago. But OW1\nLabor Board, the\nStabilization Director and other key\nagencies and individuals felt it\nwould \"not be too good\" for the\nmorale of the public to let them be\nprinted.\nHad the figures been announced,\n!t is possible that Congress could\nhave been forced to remain in Wash\nington and do something about re\nconversion, about unemployment com\npensation And the full employment\nbill.\nNow the House ways and means\ncommittee is back to Washington for\nhearings on the Truman plan to ex\ntend and expand unemployment com\npensation to cover federal and mari\ntime workers and set a uniform Hgure\nof $25 a week for 26 weeks.\nDoughton Opposed\nChairman Robert L. Doughton\n(D.N.C.) agreed to the hearings\nafter a session with Truman at the\nWhite House. He is not an advo\ncate of unemployment compensa\ntion of any kind\u2014and certainly is\nno friend of the Truman proposal.\nUndoubtedly pressure from Tru\nman and the Democratic adminis\ntration will force this tory-loaded\ncommittee to report out a bill writ\nten largely along the line suggested.\nIt is highly likely that it will be\nadopted in the face of the unrest\ncaused throughout the nation by\nthe mounting joblessness.\nBut the real danger will come after\nthe House and Senate tories begin\ncackling about what a great piece of\nliberal legislation they have hatched.\nThere will be a tendency among them\nto argue that they have solved the\nproblem\u2014and that \"our free enter\nprise system\" will do the rest and\nsolve the riddle of unemployment in\nits own individualistic manner.\nA Safety Valve\nThe expansion of unemployment\ncompensation is only a sort of safety\nvaive\u2014a tider over. Unless some real\npressures are exerted by the adminis\ntration, labor, the people and the\nhberal forces within Congress to en\nact the Murray full employment bill\nand set up a program of action for\nfederal works to get into motion if\nand when free enterprise fails to meet\nthe problem, we simply can't tell how\nmuch unemployment we face in the\ncoming winter.\nLetting the union's Washington\nlegtslatnvc representatives do the\nthat \"something\nwni be done is not the way to get\nthis problem settled.\nThe more Congress hears from\nthe workers and their wives\u2014indi\nvidually written letters detailing the\nhardships faced and demanding\nsound legislation immediately\u2014the\nquicker we can have real reconver\nsion planning.\nNEW* USED\nMATERIALS\nlowest\nAMSi^ \"\"\"DOW^\nBX CABLE\nSINKS\u2014\nMost Types\nf STINGS\nBRICKS\nTOILETS\nSINK FAUCETS\nCELLAR PUMPS\nELECTRIC FIXTURES\nBRASS PIPE\n\"\"'\"'\"S Ev.,y\n'?*yWMl]tCC,!.)\nWE WRECK AWYTHHWC\nFor Members Of\nOrganized Labor Industry\nHere Is a Public Service That Can Help You!\nWe WiH;\nWRITE YOUR SPEECHES\nWRITE YOUR REPORTS\nGET YOU NEWSPAPER PUBLICITY\nWRITE SPECIAL ARTICLES\nADVISE ON PUBLIC RELATIONS\nOur Rates Are High, And So Is The\nQuality OI Our Work\nAddress Box G\nThe Union Times\n35-139 Goffe Street, New Haven 1 1, Conn.","height":"26766","width":"20790"}}
